[[Image:DAB Digital Radio.jpg|right|thumb|200px|A typical DAB digital radio receiver with the Digital Radio Development Bureau ''DAB digital radio'' marketing logo]]
In the [[United Kingdom]], the roll-out of '''digital radio''' is proceeding since test transmissions were started by the [[BBC]] in 1990. The UK currently has the world's biggest [[digital radio]] network, with 103 transmitters, with two national [[Digital Audio Broadcasting|DAB]] [[DAB ensemble|ensembles]] and forty eight local and regional DAB ensembles broadcasting over 250 commercial and 34 BBC [[radio station]]s across the UK. In the [[Capital|capital city]] of [[London]] there are already more than 51 different digital stations available. In addition to DAB, radio stations are also broadcast on [[digital television]] platforms, [[Digital Radio Mondiale]] on [[mediumwave]] and [[shortwave]] [[frequency|frequencies]] as well as [[internet radio]] in the UK. Digital radio ensemble operators and stations need a broadcasting licence by the UK's media regulator [[Ofcom]] to broadcast.

Digital Radio in the United Kingdom is being sold by radio stations and the industry to consumers as having more choice of radio stations, ease of use, resistance to [[interference]] and the price of radios being reduced to allow mass mainstream uptake of digital radio through various platforms.<ref name="RadioAndTelly">{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandtelly.co.uk/dab.html|title=A look at DAB|accessdate=2007-07-09|publisher=Radio and Telly}}</ref> There has been concerns from individual users and the industry over the sound quality of radio stations broadcast digitally<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mysite.wanadoo-members.co.uk/freq_find/DAB_sound.html|title=Does DAB give better sound quality?|accessdate=2007-07-09|publisher=Frequency Finder UK}}</ref> as well as coverage of DAB digital radio in the UK.<ref name="RadioAndTelly" />

19.5% of the UK population own a digital radio and 58% of people have access to digital radio either through a [[Receiver (radio)|radio set]], [[television]] or [[Internet radio|online]].<ref name="percentage">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/radio/a46373/digital-radio-owners-up-43-percent.html|title=Digital radio owners up 43%|accessdate=2007-05-12|date=2007-05-10|last=Oatts|first=Joanne|publisher=Digital Spy}}</ref> The industry trade body, the Digital Radio Development Bureau, expects the number of people owning one digital radio to rise to 28.7% and the digital radio industry is expected to be valued at <U+00A3>500 million by 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/3723138.stm|title=Digital radio sales 13m 'by 2008'|accessdate=2007-07-09|date=2004-10-07|publisher=BBC Radio}}</ref>

== Digital Audio Broadcasting ==
{{seealso|Digital Audio Broadcasting|List of radio stations in the United Kingdom|DAB ensemble}}
Experimental transmissions of the DAB Eureka 147 standard from the [[Crystal Palace transmitting station]] by the BBC started in 1990<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/rd/milestones/1990s.shtml|title=Milestones - 1990s|accessdate=2007-04-17|publisher=BBC Research and Development}}</ref> with permanent transmissions covering London in [[1995|September 1995]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaleradio.nl/Catalyst/EN/articles/EN_02_TheStatusofT-DABinEurope.htm|title=The Status of T-DAB implementation in Europe|accessdate=2007-04-17|publisher=The Catalyst}}</ref> With the expansion of its [[single-frequency network]] in the spring of 1998,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/rd/projects/dab/dabbbc.shtml|title=So how does the BBC fit in?|accessdate=2007-07-09|publisher=BBC Research and Development}}</ref> the BBC national ensemble was available to 65% of the UK population by 2001 and to 85% by 2004.<ref name="BBCDCMS">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/info/policies/pdf/dab_review.pdf|title=DCMS REVIEW OF DAB DIGITAL RADIO|accessdate=2007-06-10|year=2004|month=10|publisher=BBC}}</ref>

The Broadcasting Act of 1996 allowed the introduction of national, regional and local commercial ensembles in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/ACTS/acts1996/1996055.htm|title=Broadcasting Act 1996|accessdate=2007-04-21|publisher=Her Majesty<U+2019>s Stationery Office|work=Office of Public Sector Information}}</ref>

The first national ensemble licence for DAB from the [[Ofcom|Radio Authority]] was advertised in 1998 and one applicant applied for the licence. The licence was awarded to the GWR Group, now part of [[GCap Media]], and its current owners and NTL Broadcast, who since the launch were renamed [[Arqiva]].<ref name="DigitalOne">{{cite web|url=http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/rep_pub/reports/2003/fulltext/479a3.6.pdf|title=APPENDIX 3.6 - Digital audio broadcasting|accessdate=2007-04-17|publisher=Competition Commission|format=pdf}}</ref> The two companies formed the [[Digital One]] ensemble, which began broadcasting on [[15 November]] [[1999]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/dab/tapi141.pdf|title=World DAB
Forum - DAB: a digital revolution for Europe and the World|accessdate=2007-04-17|month=11|year=1999|publisher=World DAB Forum|work=Radio Televisi<U+00F3>n Espa<U+00F1>ola|format=pdf}}</ref> The Digital One ensemble has grown and is currently available to 85% of the UK population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalone.co.uk/faq/default.asp?show=show&search=coverage|title=Frequently Asked Questions|accessdate=2007-07-09|publisher=Digital One}}</ref>

=== Growth and benefits of DAB in the UK ===
[[Image:UK digital radio listening.png|right|thumb|350px|Listeners of digital television and Internet radio and owners of DAB radio share]]
In the United Kingdom, the uptake of DAB has increased since the launch of the BBC national DAB ensemble in 1995. Lower prices, new radio stations and marketing have increased the uptake of DAB radio in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dtg.org.uk/news/news.php?id=1641|title=DAB radio sales pass 3m landmark|accessdate=2007-06-10|date=2006-05-03|publisher=Lovelace Consulting|work=Digital TV Group}}</ref> Digital radios were first sold as car radios in 1997, priced around <U+00A3>800, with hi-fi tuners costing up to <U+00A3>2000 being released two years later.<ref name="BBCDCMS" /> In 2001, Digital One invested in Frontier Silicon to produce a new processing chip which would allow cheaper portable radios to be produced. [[Roberts]], [[Goodmans]] and in 2002, [[Pure Digital]]'s award winning<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pure.com/Releases/Release.asp?ID=277|title=PURE EVOKE SERIES AWARDED GET CONNECTED <U+201C>PRODUCT OF THE YEAR<U+201D>|accessdate=2007-06-10|date=2007-02-13|publisher=Pure Digital}}</ref> Evoke series of radios broke the <U+00A3>100 price barrier, and DAB take up has increased since.<ref name="BBCDCMS" /> As the result of the increase of uptake of DAB, electrical retailer [[Dixons (UK)|Dixons]] announced in 2006 that it would discontinue selling analogue radios.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/technology/s/220/220898_dixons_turn_off_analogue_radio_supply.html|title=Dixons turn off analogue radio supply|accessdate=2007-06-10|date=2006-08-16|publisher=Manchester Evening News}}</ref>

The BBC and other DAB broadcasters have been encouraging DAB take up by promoting a number of features which are either new or improve upon former technology in their sales literature. The benefits of DAB is that due to the use of multiplexing technology and [[encoding]] technology, broadcasters including the BBC and EMAP have been able to launch exclusive digital radio stations alongside existing their analogue radio stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/digitalradio/listen/which.shtml|title=How to listen to digital radio|accessdate=2007-06-12|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emapdigitalradio.com/edr/index.shtml|title=Emap Digital Radio|accessdate=2007-06-12|publisher=EMAP}}</ref> Broadcasters also state that DAB offers better reception, without the problems of interference that is more noticeable through analogue radio.<ref name="Benefits">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/digitalradio/about/benefits.shtml|title=What is DAB digital radio?|accessdate=2007-06-12|publisher=BBC}}</ref> DAB radios also come with features such as station lists, so listeners do not need to retune their receivers, as well as scrolling text, telling listeners information such as breaking news, travel information or the latest track information.<ref name="Benefits" />

DAB has also been marketed with having two major advantages over analogue radio broadcasting in that using [[MPEG-1 Audio Layer II]] [[Audio compression (data)|lossy audio compression]] technology, parts of the audio spectrum that cannot be heard by humans are discarded, meaning less data needs to be sent over the air. This, as well as [[multiplexing]] technology allows a number of channels to be broadcast together on one frequency as opposed to one channel for analogue radio broadcasts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastpapers.com/whitepapers/paper_loader.cfm?pid=420|title=THE USE OF MORE EFFICIENT AUDIO COMPRESSION TO PROVIDE LOW BIT-RATE SPECIALIST SERVICES OVER DAB|accessdate=2007-06-12|author=I.P. Duncumb, A.L. Bridgen and J. L. Alty|publisher=Loughborough University}}</ref>

National, local and regional DAB ensembles use the same frequency for the area they cover. Using a [[single-frequency network]], an ensemble broadcasting a number of stations can cover the same area as a number of FM frequencies which would be required to cover the same area for one station. The BBC carried out tests in London of a single-frequency network with success prior to launching its national DAB ensemble. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebu.ch/en/technical/trev/trev_261-maddocks.pdf|title=Field trials with a high power VHF single frequency network for DAB|accessdate=2007-06-12|year=2004|publisher=European Broadcasting Union}}</ref>

=== Criticisms of DAB in the UK ===

UK broadcasters have used lower [[bit rate]]s to vastly increase the choice & variety of radio stations available to the public from each multiplex, leading to some criticism of reduced audio fidelity. 98% of stereo stations on DAB in the UK use a bit rate level of 128 kbps<ref>http://www.digitalradiotech.co.uk/dab/worldwide_dab.htm</ref> with the [[MP2]] audio codec. Some music stations (for example, [[theJazz]]) are transmitting in mono.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalradiotech.co.uk/articles/Mono-is-the-new-stereo-on-national-DAB.php|title=	
Mono is the new stereo on national DAB|date=2006-12-15|accessdate=2007-05-21|publisher=Digitalradiotech}}</ref> However, a recent OFCOM survey demonstrated that 94% of DAB Digital Radio listeners were satisfied with the quality of audio they were receiving.<ref>http://www.ofcom.org.uk/consult/condocs/futureradio/summary/|title=OFCOM - The Future Of Radio - DAB Sound Quality</ref>
At the Westminster Media Forum in June 2007, [[National Grid Wireless]]' general manager for broadcasting, Tony Moretta, dismissed concerns about DAB audio quality. He stated that "DAB is perfectly good enough".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.guardian.co.uk/radio/story/0,,2096010,00.html|title=DAB too pricey to go nationwide, warns BBC exec|accessdate=2007-06-06|date=2007-06-05|last=Plunkett|first=John|publisher=Media Guardian}}</ref> Indeed, [[bit rate]]s used by the radio stations on other platforms, such as cable, terrestrial and satellite is higher than on DAB, so the audio quality is higher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalradiotech.co.uk/dab/digital_radio_bit_rates.htm|title=	
Digital Radio Platform Bit Rates|accessdate=2007-05-21|publisher=Digitalradiotech}}</ref> For example, all of the [[BBC]] stations use higher bit rates on the [[digital TV]] platforms than on DAB apart from the [[BBC World Service]] on [[Freeview]].

In addition, [[Ofcom]] has said that even after extra [[spectrum]] has been allocated to DAB, it estimates that around 90 local radio stations will either be unable to transmit on DAB because there is no space for them on a local DAB multiplex or because they cannot afford the high transmission costs of DAB that the multiplex operators are charging. However, Ofcom announced in 2005 that it regarded ([[Digital Radio Mondiale]]) (DRM) as being an option for the local stations unable to secure carriage or unable to pay the high transmission costs of DAB.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/consult/condocs/radio_reviewp2/p2.pdf|title=	
Radio - Preparing for the Future - Phase 2: Implementing the Framework|date=2005-10-19|accessdate=2007-05-21|publisher=Ofcom}}</ref>

Roll-out of DAB has also not reached some areas of the UK yet. In June 2007, the BBC controller for multimedia and interactive, Mark Friend, warned that some areas of the UK may never get DAB services due to the expense of building new transmitters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/radio/a59556/dab-too-expensive-for-national-rollout.html|title= DAB 'too expensive' for national rollout|accessdate=2007-06-05|date=2007-06-05|last=Oatts|first=Joanne|publisher=Digital Spy}}</ref>

=== DAB frequency plan ===

DAB radio stations in the United Kingdom are broadcast on a number of frequency blocks on [[VHF]] [[Band III]]. The original plan devised in [[Wiesbaden]] for the framework of DAB in Europe was to allocate frequency blocks 11B to 12D for UK DAB broadcasting. However, as part of its Review of Radio, Ofcom has expanded the frequency allocations for DAB and has advertised local and a national ensemble licence on blocks outside the original Wiesbaden plan on 10A to 10D and 11A.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/consult/condocs/radio_reviewp2/appendix_d.pdf|title=Radio <U+2013> Preparing for the Future - Appendix D: Options for DAB replanning <U+2013> A report to the DRDB - Analogue Radio Switchover Group|accessdate=2007-04-21|publisher=Ofcom, Arqiva|page=9-10format=pdf}}</ref>

