Under a Maastricht plan in 2002, the UK also has [[L band]] allocations for local terrestrial DAB,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wohnort.org/DAB/uklband.html|title=L-band Allocations|accessdate=2007-04-21|Publisher=DAB Ensembles Worldwide}}</ref> though there are no plans to broadcast any digital radio stations on L band, as Ofcom are currently proposing to auction the capacity in L band in the Autumn of 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/radiocomms/spectrumawards/awardspending/award_1452/260307/design.pdf|title=Award of available spectrum1452 <U+2013>1492 MHz: Auction design|accessdate=2007-07-09|date=2007-03-26|last=Louth|first=Graham|publisher=Ofcom}}</ref>

==== BBC National DAB ====
{{main|BBC DAB National}}
The BBC's national DAB ensemble broadcasts on frequency block 12B (225.648 [[Hertz|MHz]]) across the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio-now.co.uk/national.htm|title=National radio stations in the United Kingdom|accessdate=2007-04-15|publisher=radio-now.co.uk}}</ref> with coverage currently at 85%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mysite.wanadoo-members.co.uk/freq_find/DAB_reception.html|title=Does DAB give better reception?|accessdate=2007-04-15|publisher=Frequency Finder UK and Ireland}}</ref> The multiplex is owned and operated by the BBC and is transmitted from a number of transmitter sites across the country. The BBC's national multiplex only carries BBC national [[radio station]]s. [[BBC Local Radio|Local BBC radio]] stations are carried on the relevant local DAB ensemble where commercial DAB licences are operating.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/reception/transmitters/radio/digital_local_radio.shtml|title=BBC local radio on DAB - transmitter information|accessdate=2007-04-15|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>

==== Commercial DAB multiplexes ====

There are a number of commercial DAB multiplexes operators in the UK who run 48 local and regional DAB multiplexes across the United Kingdom. operators include the national operator, [[Digital One]], regional operator MXR and local multiplexes operators including NOW Digital, [[EMAP]], [[UTV]] and Switch Digital.

== DAB+ ==

[[Digital Audio Broadcasting#DAB+|DAB+]], a new digital radio standard using the [[HE-AAC]] encoding standard and announced by the WorldDAB organisation in 2006, is being considered for digital radio broadcasting in the UK. HE-AAC encoding is more efficient than the MPEG-2 Layer II encoding standard currently used for DAB in the UK. DAB+ will either allow stations to broadcast at higher sound quality than currently possible with DAB, or allow more stations at the same quality currently broadcast on an ensemble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalradiotech.co.uk/dab/dab_vs_dab+.htm|title=DAB vs DAB+ technology|accessdate=2007-07-09|publisher=Digital Radio Tech}}</ref>

The Digital Radio Development Bureau released a [[News release|press statement]] in January that it is likely that the UK will add the DAB+ standard between 2010 and 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalradiotech.co.uk/documents/DRDB_UK_DAB+_policy.pdf|title=Optional high efficiency audio codec in the UK|accessdate=2007-04-21|publisher=Digital Radio Development Bureau|work=Digital Radio Tech}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalradiotech.co.uk/articles/UK-DAB-industry-admits-DAB+-will-be-used-in-the-UK.php|title=	
UK DAB industry admits DAB+ will be used in the UK|accessdate=2007-04-21|date=2007-03-29|publisher=Digital Radio Tech}}</ref> Ofcom have said that the UK will switch to DAB+, but not until the vast majority of radio sets can work with DAB+.

== Digital television ==
[[Image:EmleyMoorMastSpring2006.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Transmitters including [[Emley Moor transmitting station|Emley Moor]] (pictured) broadcast digital radio via DAB and digital terrestrial television]]
In the United Kingdom, 41% of digital radio users listen to digital radio through a television platform.<ref name="percentage" />

=== Digital terrestrial ===
{{seealso|Digital terrestrial television in the United Kingdom}}
Digital radio on the digital terrestrial platform started on October 30, 2002<ref>Although not strictly classed as a digital radio service, [[BBC Parliament]] broadcast on digital terrestrial in audio only up until the launch of Freeview on October 30, 2002</ref> with the launch of the BBC's digital only radio services, [[BBC 1Xtra]], [[BBC Five Live Sports Extra]], [[BBC 6 Music]], [[BBC 7]] and the [[BBC Asian Network]] as well as existing stations [[BBC Radio Five Live]] and the [[BBC World Service]]. All the stations broadcast on the BBC's [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplex]] B.

On the same day, [[EMAP]] launched three radio stations, [[Smash Hits]], [[Kerrang!]] and [[Kiss 100 London|Kiss]]. Two other [[Commercial broadcasting|commercial radio]] stations also launched, [[oneword]] and [[102.2 Jazz FM]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/10_october/03/freeview_launchdate.shtml|title=Freeview to launch on 30 October|accessdate=2007-04-15|date=2002-10-03|publisher=BBC Press Office}}</ref>

The BBC later launched [[BBC Radio 1]], [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]], [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3]] and [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4 FM]] on multiplex A on [[February 14, 2003]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/digitaltv/a10361/freeview-launch-for-radio-1-4.html|title= Freeview launch for Radio 1 - 4|accessdate=2007-04-15|date=2003-02-12|last=Wilkes|first=Neil|publisher=Digital Spy}}</ref>

Currently, the digital terrestrial platform has twenty seven radio stations broadcasting from broadcasters including the BBC, EMAP, [[GMG Radio]] and [[Virgin Radio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freeview.co.uk/channels/radio|title=Freeview - Radio|accessdate=2007-04-15|publisher=DTV Services Limited}}</ref>

=== Digital satellite ===

Radio stations broadcasting via [[Satellite]] to the United Kingdom usually use the [[SES Astra]] 2 series of satellites at 28.2<U+00B0>E or the [[Eutelsat]] [[Eurobird 1]] satellite at 28.5<U+00B0>E. Radio stations broadcast [[free-to-air]] via the [[Sky Digital (UK & Ireland)|Sky Digital]], [[Freesat from Sky]], the planned [[Freesat]] platforms and any [[DVB-S]] compliant [[set-top box]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/satellite/freesatepg/|title=Sky Digital - Freesat: Channel Lineup|accessdate=2007-04-16|publisher=Digital Spy}}</ref>

=== Digital cable ===

A number of digital radio stations also broadcast through [[digital cable]] platforms, including [[Virgin Media]] and [[WightCable]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-dab.info/dcable.php|title=Digital cable|accessdate=2007-04-16|publisher=RJ Productions}}</ref>

== Internet radio ==

In the United Kingdom, over 350 of the UK's radio stations also [[streaming media|stream]] their stations online, not including [[Restricted Service Licence]]d radio stations, [[Hospital radio]] stations and stations who solely broadcast online.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiofeeds.co.uk|title=UK Radio Stations broadcasting on the Internet|accessdate=2007-05-12|last=Lo|first=Vincent|publisher=Radiofeeds.co.uk}}</ref> 24.3% of digital radio users listen to radio online.<ref name="percentage" /> As well as listening through a [[media player]] on a [[computer]], a number of British firms, including [[BT Group]], Reciva, Dixons and Acoustic Energy have brought out [[Internet radio device]]s which use the [[Wi-Fi]] signal from a router to stream Internet radio stations within range of a Wi-Fi router.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theregister.com/2004/04/23/net_radios/|title=Firms prep Wi-Fi Internet radio tuners|accessdate=2007-06-12|date=2004-04-23|last=Smith|first=Tony|publisher=The Register}}</ref>

In 2006, the [[Phonographic Performance Limited]] (PPL) announced that it would charge additional royalty fees on UK [[Internet radio]] stations if they broadcast outside the UK.<ref name="PPL">{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundnewseurope.com/pdf/psne_download/2006/09/PSNE_September_P25-28_Broadcast.pdf|title=UK streamed radio blocked by copyright|accessdate=2007-04-19|month=09|year=2006|last=Hilton|first=Kevin|page=25|publisher=Pro Sound News Europe|format=pdf}}</ref> Radio stations which stream online including [[GCap Media]] and [[GMG Radio]]<ref>The exception to this is [[jazzfm.com]], which continues to be streamed outside the UK</ref>, have implemented [[IP blocking]] to prevent listeners outside the UK from listening to their radio stations and therefore avoided the increased fees.<ref name="PPL" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://media.guardian.co.uk/newmedia/story/0,,1767058,00.html|title=Will licensing kill the radio star?|accessdate=2007-04-19|date=2006-05-04|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>

In March 2007, a [[BBC News]] article reported that the PPL were re-negotiating royalty fees paid by UK Internet radio stations, and the result of the negotiations would be that fees would increase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6430489.stm|title=Royalties threaten internet radio|accessdate=2007-04-19|date=2007-03-08|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

== Digital Radio Mondiale ==

[[Digital Radio Mondiale]] is being considered by [[Ofcom]] for introduction in [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in 2012 on the present AM medium wave band. 

In 2005, tests of DRM on [[shortwave]] radio from European transmitters broadcasting into the United Kingdom were performed by [[Virgin Radio]], [[Classic Gold]], [[Premier Christian Radio]], [[Virgin Radio Classic Rock]], Asian Sound and CVC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drmradio.co.uk/html/drm_uk.html|title=DRM UK|accessdate=2007-04-21|publisher=DRMRadio}}</ref>

The British Broadcasting Corporation [[BBC]] started broadcasting the BBC World Service on shortwave and [[mediumwave]] radio  for a few hours a day<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/faq/news/story/2005/09/050907_drm_launch_release.shtml|title=BBC Launches DRM Service In Europe|accessdate=2007-04-21|date=2005-09-07|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> across Europe from [[Orfordness transmitting station|Orford Ness]] in Suffolk and [[Kvits<U+00F8>y]] in Norway, the latter being receivable across England, Wales and Southern Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drm.org/livebroadcast/livebroadcast.php|title=Live Broadcasts Schedule|accessdate=2007-04-21|publisher=Digital Radio Mondiale}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://baseportal.com/cgi-bin/baseportal.pl?htx=/drmdx/details&cmd=all&Id==199|title=DRM Schedule - Kvitsoy|accessdate=2007-04-21|publisher=DRM DX}}</ref>

The BBC has announced that it is to undertake a trial of the digital radio mondiale (DRM) technology, which will allow it to explore digital radio using medium-wave frequencies.
The trial will broadcast [[BBC Radio Devon]] using the new technology in the Plymouth area and will last for a year from the end of April 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/digitalmediumwave/index.shtml|title=Digital Medium Wave|accessdate=2007-04-15|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref>

== Digital Multimedia Broadcasting ==

In 2006, [[National Grid Wireless]] carried out a technical trial of [[Digital Multimedia Broadcasting|T-DMB]] and DAB-IP on the [[UTV-EMAP Stoke-on-Trent]] ensemble.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk.nationalgridwireless.com/downloads/NGW_info_sheet.pdf|title=Mobile media test at Stoke (T-DMB and DAB-IP service)|accessdate=2007-04-19|publisher=National Grid Wireless|format=pdf}}</ref> The trial assessed the reception qualities of both technologies in urban and rural areas as well as the [[Telematics|mobile television]] and radio services which could be delivered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk.nationalgridwireless.com/pr_20060909.shtml|title=National Grid Wireless begins DAB-IP and T-DMB trial|accessdate=2007-04-19|date=2006-09-09|publisher=National Grid Wireless}}</ref>

== Application and licensing ==

The United Kingdom media and communications [[Ofcom]] (and before the formation of Ofcom, the Radio Authority) advertises and provides the licenses for digital radio services in the United Kingdom, under the Broadcasting Acts of 1990 and 1996.<ref name="procedure">{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/archive/rau/about-ra/factsheets/fs3.html|title=THE RADIO AUTHORITY : ITS LICENCES AND LICENSING PROCEDURES|accessdate=2007-05-05|publisher=Radio Authority|work=Ofcom}}</ref>

=== Application and licensing procedures ===

Ofcom awards licenses for digital radio services differently depending on the type of service and the platform.<ref name="procedure" /> Ofcom advertises the licences of new digital radio ensembles and are subject to an [[auction|open competition]] to the highest bidder. Ensemble licence awards are awarded for twelve years. On digital television services, individual stations can apply for either a digital cable and satellite licence to broadcast on the aforementioned platforms<ref name="procedure" />, or apply for a digital terrestrial licence to broadcast on digital terrestrial television.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/tvlicensing/dtt/main.htm|title=TV Licensing - Digital terrestrial television|accessdate=2007-05-12|publisher=Ofcom}}</ref>

=== First national ensemble ===

On March 24, 1998, the Radio Authority advertised for the first (and at the time, the only one planned) national ensemble to be broadcast on DAB. The three national commercial services on FM and mediumwave had to be included as part of the ensemble, [[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]], [[talkSPORT]] and [[Virgin Radio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/archive/rau/newsroom/news-release/98/pr17.htm|title=RADIO AUTHORITY ANNOUNCES ADVERTISEMENT DATE FOR NATIONAL COMMERCIAL MULTIPLEX|accessdate=2007-05-05|date=1998-03-05|publisher=Radio Authority|work=Ofcom}}</ref> The licence was awarded to the sole applicant, GWR Group and NTL Broadcast to form Digital One.<ref name="DigitalOne" /> The original licence application included the following stations:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/archive/rau/newsroom/news-release/98/pr56.htm|title=RADIO AUTHORITY RECEIVES ONE APPLICATION FOR FIRST AND ONLY NATIONAL COMMERCIAL DIGITAL MULTIPLEX LICENCE|accessdate=2007-05-12|publisher=Radio Authority|work=Ofcom}}</ref>

